02:25.738 --> 02:28.374
It's funny... I never pictured
your mom as the retiring type.

02:28.375 --> 02:30.143
I always figured when
the time was right,

02:30.144 --> 02:32.978
someone would throw water on
her, and she'd just melt away.

02:34.247 --> 02:36.949
I know... she loved working
at the school cafeteria.

02:36.950 --> 02:39.818
And she could rock a hairnet.

02:39.820 --> 02:41.187
So how does she seem?

02:41.188 --> 02:42.488
I mean, is she excited?

02:42.489 --> 02:43.790
Is she making plans?

02:43.791 --> 02:45.158
Is she gonna travel?
(gasps)

02:45.159 --> 02:47.359
Ooh, maybe she'll move
to Florida.

02:48.561 --> 02:49.795
Yeah, well, if she does,

02:49.796 --> 02:51.230
it'll give those
old geezers in Boca

02:51.231 --> 02:52.898
something to bitch about
besides the humidity.

02:52.900 --> 02:55.667
So are you gonna
throw her a party?

02:55.669 --> 02:58.803
Molly, we don't know for sure
that she's moving to Florida.

02:58.805 --> 03:00.406
No.

03:00.407 --> 03:01.807
For... for the retirement.

03:01.808 --> 03:03.075
I mean, you're her son.

03:03.076 --> 03:04.609
Don't you think you should
plan something?

03:04.611 --> 03:06.012
I'm not good
at that kind of thing.

03:06.013 --> 03:07.278
Oh, it's easy.
You just...

03:07.280 --> 03:09.515
invite her friends from work,
you get a sheet cake,

03:09.516 --> 03:11.417
you sing her
"For She's a Jolly Good Fellow,"

03:11.418 --> 03:12.651
the monster's appeased,

03:12.652 --> 03:15.854
then the villagers are safe
until the next harvest.

03:15.856 --> 03:18.591
You know what,
a party is a great idea.

03:18.592 --> 03:19.592
Well, thank you.

03:19.593 --> 03:20.860
No. Thank you.

03:20.861 --> 03:22.760
You're gonna make my mother
very happy.

03:22.762 --> 03:24.163
Let me know if you need me
to pick up

03:24.164 --> 03:25.498
that cake that you order.

03:25.499 --> 03:26.832
Wait, wait, wait, wait, what?

03:26.833 --> 03:28.666
You're a good daughter-in-law.

03:29.702 --> 03:31.237
What the hell just happened?

03:31.238 --> 03:33.972
You got duped by a dope.

03:41.213 --> 03:42.548
Surprise!

03:42.549 --> 03:43.715
Hey.

03:43.717 --> 03:45.017
If you're with the
health department,

03:45.018 --> 03:46.919
you need to give
us 48 hours notice.

03:46.920 --> 03:48.887
We know the law.

03:48.888 --> 03:51.857
No, it's Molly Flynn.

03:51.858 --> 03:53.859
I-I taught here for,
like, ten years.

03:53.860 --> 03:55.092
Uh-uh, uh-uh.

03:55.094 --> 03:56.128
Miss Flynn?

03:56.129 --> 03:57.095
Taught fourth grade?

03:57.096 --> 03:59.731
Teacher of the Year?

03:59.732 --> 04:02.300
Green salad with a scoop
of tuna on the side?

04:02.302 --> 04:04.369
Ah.
Oh, hey, honey.

04:04.370 --> 04:05.536
How you doing?

04:05.538 --> 04:06.705
Good, good.

04:06.706 --> 04:09.341
Uh, anyway, the reason
I'm here is

04:09.342 --> 04:11.776
because you are both invited
to a party.

04:11.778 --> 04:12.911
Oh, hey.
Ooh.

04:12.912 --> 04:14.378
Yeah, to celebrate
Peggy's retirement.

04:14.380 --> 04:15.413
(chuckles)

04:15.415 --> 04:17.749
Yay.

04:17.750 --> 04:19.784
Party.

04:20.886 --> 04:22.287
Is this some sort of joke?

04:22.288 --> 04:23.555
No, but it is a secret.

04:23.556 --> 04:25.323
So don't tell
the one-eyed janitor,

04:25.324 --> 04:27.758
(whispering):
'cause he's not invited.

04:27.760 --> 04:29.728
Look, tuna scoop,

04:29.729 --> 04:31.229
I don't know
what Peggy told you,

04:31.230 --> 04:33.031
but she didn't retire;
she got fired.

04:33.032 --> 04:34.866
What?
Yep.

04:34.867 --> 04:37.502
That woman was the worst person
I've ever had to deal with.

04:37.503 --> 04:40.738
And I used to work
the chow line at Joliet.

04:42.140 --> 04:43.441
When she started working here,

04:43.442 --> 04:46.276
she was warm, friendly,
just like us.

04:48.012 --> 04:50.515
But once she got promoted
to griddle master,

04:50.516 --> 04:52.616
the power went
straight to her head.

04:52.618 --> 04:54.318
Oh, I remember that.

04:54.320 --> 04:56.054
There was a couple months
where she insisted

04:56.055 --> 04:57.255
we call her "the Griddler."

04:57.256 --> 04:58.223
Ugh.

04:58.224 --> 05:00.158
She was horrible.

05:00.159 --> 05:03.194
She would peck away
at every minor flaw you had.

05:03.195 --> 05:05.563
Do you have any idea
what it's like to live

05:05.564 --> 05:07.165
under that kind of scrutiny?

05:07.166 --> 05:09.800
I married into
that kind of scrutiny.

05:09.802 --> 05:12.470
It became such a hostile
work environment,

05:12.471 --> 05:13.805
we went to the principal.

05:13.806 --> 05:14.871
She had to go.
Mmm.

05:14.873 --> 05:17.275
Your mother-in-law
learned a hard lesson

05:17.276 --> 05:19.243
about cafeteria life.

05:19.244 --> 05:22.813
Fly too high, and the
heat lamps gonna get ya.

05:25.249 --> 05:26.784
That's a good one.

05:26.785 --> 05:30.387
So it-it was time for her
to tapioca out of here.

05:33.057 --> 05:34.457
Yours was better.
Mmm.

05:34.459 --> 05:36.259
It was better.

05:37.828 --> 05:39.197
MOLLY: Mike!

05:39.198 --> 05:40.498
In here.

05:40.499 --> 05:42.365
Ooh, you better sit down.

05:43.868 --> 05:44.868
Okay.

05:44.870 --> 05:45.836
'Cause this is big.

05:45.837 --> 05:47.337
This is juicy.

05:47.339 --> 05:49.006
And I don't like throwing
around the word "bombshell,"

05:49.007 --> 05:50.874
but bombshell.

05:51.876 --> 05:53.376
Well, what is it?

05:53.378 --> 05:55.746
Okay, here we go.

05:55.747 --> 05:58.382
Your mom did not retire.

05:58.383 --> 06:00.417
She was fired.

06:00.418 --> 06:02.252
(imitates explosion)

06:06.857 --> 06:09.160
And...?

06:09.161 --> 06:10.127
And?

06:10.128 --> 06:11.629
Are you kidding me?

06:11.630 --> 06:12.963
Your mom was fired.

06:12.964 --> 06:14.564
She lied right to your face.

06:14.566 --> 06:16.099
Eh, she does that.

06:17.710 --> 06:18.869
That's it?

06:18.870 --> 06:20.037
That's all you're gonna give me?

06:20.038 --> 06:21.839
I'm sorry,
but this is nothing new.

06:21.840 --> 06:23.640
She spins every negative thing
in her life

06:23.641 --> 06:24.875
so it isn't her fault.

06:24.876 --> 06:26.110
But we don't call it lying.

06:26.111 --> 06:28.277
We call it "Mom's version."

06:30.047 --> 06:33.650
And in her defense, how else
is she gonna live with herself?

06:33.651 --> 06:35.619
Wait, n-n-no, we need to
confront her about this.

06:35.620 --> 06:37.120
I mean, by "we," I mean you,

06:37.121 --> 06:39.223
but I want to be there to watch.

06:39.224 --> 06:42.024
I am not confronting her.

06:42.026 --> 06:43.727
Uh, why not?

06:43.728 --> 06:45.028
Well, I don't know.

06:45.029 --> 06:46.063
Survival?

06:46.064 --> 06:47.130
Self-preservation?

06:47.131 --> 06:48.098
I'm scared of her?

06:48.099 --> 06:49.732
Take your pick.

06:49.734 --> 06:52.836
Well, I am not throwing
"Liar, liar,

06:52.837 --> 06:55.304
I didn't even retire" a party.

06:56.339 --> 06:57.707
Oh, yes, you are.

06:57.708 --> 06:59.576
As far as everyone's concerned,
she's retired.

06:59.577 --> 07:00.744
But it's not true.

07:00.745 --> 07:01.711
"But, but, but."

07:01.712 --> 07:03.679
The truth has no place here.

07:04.748 --> 07:06.449
But we will give
my mother that party,

07:06.450 --> 07:08.984
she will be ungrateful,
and we will move on.

07:09.786 --> 07:12.556
How did you survive
your childhood?

07:12.557 --> 07:13.657
What does it look like?

07:13.658 --> 07:15.591
Eating right and exercising.

